  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Farewell Discourse for Seon the Monk
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have heard it said that the Buddha does not sleep three nights beneath the same mulberry tree—wandering is indeed their way. Yet there are times of order and times of chaos, paths that open and paths that close. One cannot stumble blindly through darkness without risking danger and disaster. How many spend their whole lives with their dreams unfulfilled? Fortunate are those born into an age of shared ways and shared script, where traveling from Yue to Yan is like crossing from hall to courtyard, where riding boats through water and treading mountains in sandals, sleeping under stars and dining on wind, feels like resting at home. Is this not joy? Even the frog in the common reed cannot leap across, yet the great Peng soars ninety thousand miles. Thus we may know the measure of such spirit. What of one who seeks a master and pursues the Way, forgetting food when eating, forgetting sleep when resting, steadfastly determined to reach the Other Shore?

    Seon the Monk—I met him twice upon the Ri River. He comes from a family of officials, schooled in books and letters. At twenty-one, he accompanied a local monk to Diamond Mountain. Along the way, he heard that the Lazy Sage dwelt on Mount Taishan. He said: "Though I wish to see the mountains, renouncing the world is harder still. Finding the Lazy Sage is hardest of all. Let me first leave the world under his guidance, then visit the mountains." He entered and beseeched the master, who cut his hair with his own hands. His parents, hearing the news, wept at first, then found peace. They journeyed to Diamond Mountain to see him and said: "Since you have done this, you must take the monastic examination." The monk replied: "Why take the monastic examination? Better to take the civil examination. I left the world to study the Way. Can the Way be examined?" Pointing to his father, he said: "My father is Heaven itself. Should my resolve waver, Heaven must send punishment." His father nodded, wept deeply, and departed.

    From that time, Seon's learning deepened and his name grew renowned. Among his peers, none dared compare themselves to him. Yet still he felt it insufficient and wished to wander the world entire—his ambitions are great indeed. He asked urgently for my words. What could I say? When paths diverge, counsel falters. Yet when we meet not once but twice, affection grows—such is human nature. At parting, how could I remain silent? So I spoke to him thus:

    "Those who advance swiftly also retreat swiftly. Seon, be warned. For those who walk a hundred miles, ninety is the halfway point. Seon, persevere. To begin with vigor and end in sloth is the shared affliction of both Confucian and Buddhist. Let us both be warned and steadfast. As for the Way itself—when you return and seek it, there will be teachers to guide you still."
  footnotes:
    - The Buddha's teaching not to sleep three nights in the same place refers to the monastic practice of constant wandering and non-attachment to fixed dwelling.
    - Yue and Yan refer to ancient Chinese kingdoms; the reference suggests ease of travel during peaceful, unified times.
    - The frog and the great Peng are from Zhuangzi, symbolizing limited versus limitless potential.
    - The Other Shore (彼岸) is a Buddhist term for enlightenment or nirvana.
    - The 'Lazy Sage' (懶翁) appears to be a respected Zen master of the time.
    - The monastic and civil examinations were competitive testing systems in medieval Korea.
    - The final line suggests that even outside one's immediate teacher, wisdom and guidance will remain available to the sincere seeker.
